Neurons and  Nerve  Impulses 	  The nervous system is made up of nerves. A nerve is a bundle of nerve cells. A nerve cell that carries messages is called a neuron ( Figure 11.73). The messages carried by neurons are called nerve impulses. Nerve impulses can travel very quickly because they are electrical impulses. Think about flipping on a light switch when you enter a room. When you flip the switch, the electricity flows to the light through wires inside the walls. The electricity may have to travel many meters to reach the light, but the light still comes on as soon as you flip the switch. Nerve impulses travel just as fast through the network of nerves inside the body. 
